Questions will include the alleged capture of state-owned enterprises and the withdrawal from SA of auto manufacture general motors. CAPE TOWN - Deputy President Cyril Ramaphosa is set to face some tough questions in the National Assembly on Wednesday afternoon.They include questions from African National Congress (ANC) Members of Parliament on the alleged capture of state-owned enterprises and the withdrawal from South Africa of auto manufacture general motors.The deputy president will be asked by the African Christian Democratic Party (ACDP) if he agrees with former president Kgalema Motlanthe that the political crisis in the country is due to an absence of ethical leadership.ANC MP Mondli Gungubele wants to know how the government plans to prevent what he calls the corporate capture of state-owned entities and how public confidence in them can be restored.The Freedom Front Plus will be raising the plight of pensioners falling into poverty because, the party claims, the government is not paying towards the pension funds of the state-owned companies they once worked for.This is Ramaphosa s final question-and-answer session before Parliament s winter recess.It will be President Jacob Zuma s turn to answer questions next Thursday.(Edited by Winnie Theletsane)